---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import Navigation from '@/components/Navigation.astro';
import Footer from '@/components/Footer.astro';
import { Shield, Ruler, AlertTriangle } from 'lucide-astro';
---

<Layout title="Keyway in Footings | Complete Construction Guide">
  <Navigation />
  
  <main>
    <!-- Hero Section -->
    <section class="bg-gray-100 pt-24 pb-12">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-4xl">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
            <a href="/" class="hover:text-red-600">Home</a>
            <span>/</span>
            <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-red-600">Blog</a>
            <span>/</span>
            <span>Keyway Construction</span>
          </div>
          <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
            Keyway in Footings: Purpose, Design & Construction
          </h1>
          <p class="text-xl text-gray-600">
            Essential guide to keyway construction for foundation wall stability
          </p>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mt-4 text-sm text-gray-500">
            <span>Published: January 2024</span>
            <span>•</span>
            <span>14 min read</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <article class="py-12">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <!-- Introduction -->
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-12">
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-700 mb-8">
              A keyway is more than just a groove in concrete - it's a critical structural element that prevents 
              foundation walls from sliding under lateral earth pressure. After pouring thousands of footings in 
              Toronto's challenging clay soils, we've learned that a properly formed keyway can mean the difference 
              between a stable foundation and catastrophic wall movement. Here's everything contractors and 
              homeowners need to know about keyway design and construction.
            </p>

            <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8 border-2 border-blue-400">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
                <Shield class="w-5 h-5 text-blue-600" />
                What Is a Keyway?
              </h3>
              <p class="text-gray-700">
                A keyway is a longitudinal groove formed or cut in the top surface of a footing that creates a 
                mechanical interlock between the footing and the foundation wall. This shear key resists horizontal 
                sliding forces from earth pressure, water pressure, and frost action.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Why Keyways Matter -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
              Why Keyways Are Critical in Toronto
            </h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-8 border-2 border-gray-300">
              <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Forces Acting on Foundation Walls</h3>
              
              <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Lateral Earth Pressure:</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Clay soil: 480 kg/m³ equivalent fluid pressure</li>
                    <li>• 2.4m wall height = 11.5 kPa at base</li>
                    <li>• Increases with moisture content</li>
                    <li>• Can double with frost or saturation</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Without Keyway:</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Relies on friction alone</li>
                    <li>• Friction coefficient: 0.4-0.5</li>
                    <li>• May not resist full lateral load</li>
                    <li>• Risk of wall sliding at base</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6 border border-yellow-400">
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Toronto Clay Factor:</strong> Our expansive clay soils create variable lateral pressures. 
                  When clay gets wet, it expands and increases pressure. When it dries, it shrinks. This cycling 
                  creates moving loads that can gradually push walls off footings without proper keying.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Keyway Specifications -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
              <Ruler class="inline w-6 h-6 text-red-600 mr-2" />
              Standard Keyway Dimensions
            </h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-8 border-2 border-gray-300 mb-6">
              <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">OBC Requirements</h3>
              
              <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Minimum Dimensions:</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Width at top: 50mm (2")</li>
                    <li>• Depth: 40mm (1.5") minimum</li>
                    <li>• Shape: Trapezoidal (wider at base)</li>
                    <li>• Angle: 45-60° from vertical</li>
                    <li>• Location: Centered on footing</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Recommended Practice:</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Width: 1/3 of wall thickness</li>
                    <li>• Depth: 50mm (2") preferred</li>
                    <li>• Continuous along entire footing</li>
                    <li>• No gaps at corners</li>
                    <li>• Smooth, clean surfaces</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-gray-200">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 p-4 bg-gray-50">Keyway Sizes for Common Wall Thicknesses</h3>
              <table class="w-full">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Wall Thickness</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Keyway Width (top)</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Keyway Depth</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Form Size</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200">
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">150mm (6")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">50mm (2")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">40mm (1.5")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">2x2 beveled</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">200mm (8")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">65mm (2.5")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">50mm (2")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">2x3 beveled</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">250mm (10")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">75mm (3")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">50mm (2")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">2x3 beveled</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">300mm (12")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">100mm (4")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">60mm (2.5")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">2x4 beveled</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Construction Methods -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Keyway Construction Methods</h2>
            
            <div class="space-y-6">
              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Method 1: Wood Form (Most Common)</h3>
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Materials:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• 2x2 or 2x3 lumber</li>
                      <li>• Beveled 45° on both sides</li>
                      <li>• Treated or oiled for release</li>
                      <li>• Stakes every 1.2m (4')</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Installation:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Center on footing forms</li>
                      <li>• Secure with nails through form</li>
                      <li>• Check alignment with string</li>
                      <li>• Remove at initial set (2-4 hrs)</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Method 2: Metal Form</h3>
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Advantages:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Reusable hundreds of times</li>
                      <li>• Consistent dimensions</li>
                      <li>• Easy to clean and oil</li>
                      <li>• Won't swell or warp</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Installation:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Clip to footing forms</li>
                      <li>• No additional stakes needed</li>
                      <li>• Apply form release oil</li>
                      <li>• Remove at initial set</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Method 3: Plastic/Foam Forms</h3>
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Types:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• Extruded polystyrene strips</li>
                      <li>• Pre-formed plastic channels</li>
                      <li>• Leave-in-place systems</li>
                      <li>• Custom-cut rigid foam</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Benefits:</h4>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                      <li>• No removal required</li>
                      <li>• Acts as water stop</li>
                      <li>• Lightweight handling</li>
                      <li>• No form oil needed</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Method 4: Hand-Formed (Small Jobs)</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li>• Use edging tool or trowel</li>
                  <li>• Form groove in fresh concrete</li>
                  <li>• Requires experienced finisher</li>
                  <li>• Difficult to maintain consistency</li>
                  <li>• Only for small residential projects</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Installation Process -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Step-by-Step Installation</h2>
            
            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">1</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Prepare Keyway Form</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Cut 2x2 or 2x3 lumber to footing length. Bevel both edges at 45° using table saw or hand plane. 
                      Sand smooth. Apply form oil or diesel fuel for easy release. For reusable forms, use metal or plastic.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">2</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Position on Footing Form</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Center keyway form on footing width. Use measuring tape at multiple points. String line for 
                      alignment on long runs. Mark center of footing forms with chalk line for reference.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">3</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Secure Form</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Nail through footing forms into keyway form every 600mm. Use duplex nails for easy removal. 
                      Alternative: wire tie to rebar if present. Check level - keyway should follow footing top elevation.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">4</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Pour Concrete</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Place concrete carefully around keyway form. Avoid displacing form with concrete flow. 
                      Consolidate with vibrator, especially under keyway edges. Level flush with top of keyway form.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">5</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Initial Finishing</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Float concrete surface level with keyway form top. Don't overwork - this brings excess water 
                      to surface. Smooth transition at keyway edges. No need for perfect finish - wall will cover.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">6</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Remove Form (Critical Timing)</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Remove when concrete can hold shape but is still green (2-4 hours typically). Test edge with 
                      finger - should be firm but impressionable. Lift straight up to avoid damaging edges. 
                      Clean form immediately for reuse.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">7</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Clean and Inspect</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Remove any fins or loose concrete in keyway. Check depth and width meet specifications. 
                      Ensure continuous path - no blockages. Clean out any debris before wall pour. 
                      Document with photos for inspection.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Alternative to Keyways -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Alternatives to Keyways</h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-8 border border-gray-200">
              <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Dowel Method</h3>
              
              <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Specifications:</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Bar size: 15M minimum</li>
                    <li>• Spacing: 600mm (24") o.c.</li>
                    <li>• Embedment: 300mm into footing</li>
                    <li>• Projection: 600mm into wall</li>
                    <li>• Location: Center of wall</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">When to Use:</h4>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>• Reinforced walls</li>
                    <li>• High lateral loads</li>
                    <li>• Seismic requirements</li>
                    <li>• Existing footing connections</li>
                    <li>• ICF construction</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6 border border-yellow-400">
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Note:</strong> Dowels provide both shear resistance and tension capacity, making them 
                  superior to keyways in some applications. However, they require precise placement and add labor cost.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Common Problems -->
          <div class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-8 mb-12 border-2 border-red-200">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6 flex items-center gap-2">
              <AlertTriangle class="w-6 h-6 text-red-600" />
              Common Keyway Problems & Solutions
            </h2>
            
            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Off-Center Keyway</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  <strong>Problem:</strong> Keyway not aligned with wall center, reducing effectiveness by 50%
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Solution:</strong> Mark footing center before pour. Use string line. Check at multiple points. 
                  If discovered after pour, may need to chip and reform or use dowels.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Shallow or Filled Keyway</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  <strong>Problem:</strong> Concrete slumps into keyway, reducing depth
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Solution:</strong> Remove form at proper time. Clean immediately after removal. 
                  For existing shallow keyways, roughen surface and use bonding agent.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Damaged Edges</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  <strong>Problem:</strong> Edges break when removing form too late or too early
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Solution:</strong> Time removal correctly (2-4 hours). Pull straight up. 
                  Repair minor damage with mortar. Major damage may require chipping out and reforming.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Discontinuous Keyway</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  <strong>Problem:</strong> Gaps at corners or joints reduce effectiveness
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Solution:</strong> Miter corners at 45°. Overlap forms at joints. 
                  For existing gaps, drill and epoxy dowels at 300mm centers across gap.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Water in Keyway</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  <strong>Problem:</strong> Rain fills keyway before wall pour, weakening bond
                </p>
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  <strong>Solution:</strong> Cover footings after pour. Pump out water before wall pour. 
                  Dry with compressed air. May need to apply bonding agent if saturated.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Quality Control -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Quality Control Checklist</h2>
            
            <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-8">
              <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                <div>
                  <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Before Concrete Pour:</h3>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>☐ Keyway form centered on footing</li>
                    <li>☐ Proper dimensions (width/depth)</li>
                    <li>☐ Form oiled or treated</li>
                    <li>☐ Securely fastened</li>
                    <li>☐ Level with footing top</li>
                    <li>☐ Continuous at corners</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">After Form Removal:</h3>
                  <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                    <li>☐ Clean keyway channel</li>
                    <li>☐ Check depth (40mm minimum)</li>
                    <li>☐ Verify width (50mm minimum)</li>
                    <li>☐ Edges intact, not damaged</li>
                    <li>☐ No blockages or debris</li>
                    <li>☐ Document with photos</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
              
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Inspector Requirements:</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700">
                  Toronto Building Inspectors will verify keyway dimensions during footing inspection. Have 
                  approved drawings showing keyway details. Be prepared to demonstrate depth and width. 
                  Clean keyway before inspection - debris hiding dimensions will fail inspection.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Cost Analysis -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Cost Comparison</h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-gray-200">
              <table class="w-full">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Method</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Material Cost</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Labor</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">Total/Linear Meter</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200">
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Wood keyway form</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$2</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$8</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 font-semibold">$10</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Metal reusable form</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$0.50</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$6</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 font-semibold">$6.50</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Foam leave-in</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$4</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$5</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 font-semibold">$9</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Dowels (15M @ 600mm)</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$8</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">$12</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 font-semibold">$20</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
            
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mt-4">
              * Costs based on 40m perimeter foundation. Metal forms amortized over 100 uses.
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- Conclusion -->
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">The Bottom Line on Keyways</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
              A properly formed keyway adds about $400 to a typical residential foundation but provides critical 
              insurance against wall sliding - especially in Toronto's clay soils. The cost of fixing a wall that 
              has moved off its footing starts at $30,000 and can exceed $100,000 if the structure above is damaged.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
              In 39 years, we've never seen a properly keyed wall slide off its footing. We have, however, repaired 
              dozens of foundations where keyways were omitted, undersized, or improperly formed. The few hundred 
              dollars saved by skipping the keyway isn't worth the risk.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              At Toronto Concrete, every footing gets a properly sized and positioned keyway. We use metal forms 
              for consistency, remove them at the right time, and clean the channel before wall placement. It's a 
              small detail that makes a huge difference in foundation performance.
